                <fr:title text="Intuition: Measure vs Metric">Intuition: Measure vs Metric</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
A <html:strong>measure</html:strong> assigns a "size" to a set — how much stuff is in it. Length, area, volume, and probability are all measures.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
A <html:strong>metric</html:strong> assigns a "distance" between two points — how far apart they are.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
They answer fundamentally different questions: measure asks "how big is this region?" while metric asks "how far apart are these two points?"
</html:p>
                <html:p>
A metric is upstream of measure: a <fr:link href="/gtop-0003/" title="Metric Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0003/" display-uri="gtop-0003" type="local">metric</fr:link> defines <fr:link href="/gtop-000S/" title="Open Ball" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000S/" display-uri="gtop-000S" type="local">open balls</fr:link>, which give a <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topology</fr:link>, which give a <fr:link href="/gtop-000K/" title="Borel \sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000K/" display-uri="gtop-000K" type="local">Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link>, which gives sets you can measure. A set can be small in measure but wide in metric (e.g., a thin line segment across a room).
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
