                <fr:title text="Intuition: \sigma -algebra">Intuition: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
A <fr:link href="/gtop-000M/" title="\sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000M/" display-uri="gtop-000M" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link> is a collection of sets that is closed under the operations you need to do measurement: complements and countable unions.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Think of it as a budget of measurable sets — it decides what you are allowed to measure. Not every subset needs to be included, but whatever is included must be self-consistent: if you can measure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, you can measure "not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>"; if you can measure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_1, A_2, A_3, \ldots ]]></fr:tex>, you can measure their union.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Why not just measure everything? In <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, you cannot assign a consistent length to all subsets (Vitali sets). The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra avoids this by restricting to a well-behaved collection where measurement stays consistent.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex> specifically means countable — closed under countable unions, not just finite ones. This is what distinguishes it from a plain algebra of sets and is essential for doing limits and integration.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
