                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://boatnotabot.com/todo-0006/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>todo-0006</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/todo-0006/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intuition: Borel Measure">Intuition: Borel Measure</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
A <fr:link href="/gtop-000C/" title="Borel Measure" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000C/" display-uri="gtop-000C" type="local">Borel measure</fr:link> assigns "sizes" (lengths, areas, volumes, probabilities) to sets built from <fr:link href="/gtop-0005/" title="Open Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0005/" display-uri="gtop-0005" type="local">open sets</fr:link>.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
The <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topology</fr:link> tells you what is open, the <fr:link href="/gtop-000K/" title="Borel \sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000K/" display-uri="gtop-000K" type="local">Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link> tells you what is measurable, and a Borel measure tells you how big. It is a function that assigns a non-negative size to each <fr:link href="/gtop-000L/" title="Borel Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000L/" display-uri="gtop-000L" type="local">Borel set</fr:link>, respecting the rule that the measure of a countable disjoint union equals the sum of the measures.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Why not measure all subsets? In spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, there exist pathological sets (via the axiom of choice) that cannot be assigned a size consistently. The Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra avoids this by only including sets constructible from open sets through countable operations — which turns out to be rich enough for essentially all practical purposes.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
